{"identifier":{"interfaceLanguage":"swift","url":"doc:\/\/SwiftQL\/documentation\/SwiftQL\/Queries"},"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/SwiftQL\/documentation\/SwiftQL"],["doc:\/\/SwiftQL\/documentation\/SwiftQL","doc:\/\/SwiftQL\/documentation\/SwiftQL\/Documentation"]]},"schemaVersion":{"patch":0,"minor":3,"major":0},"sections":[],"abstract":[{"text":"Use joins, aggregates, sorting, subqueries, and common table expressions.","type":"text"}],"primaryContentSections":[{"kind":"content","content":[{"anchor":"Overview","level":2,"type":"heading","text":"Overview"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftQL\/documentation\/SwiftQL\/GettingStarted","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" showed the fundamental principles behind SwiftQL. This"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"guide covers:"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"items":[{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Joining tables"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Performing aggregate queries using group by and having clauses"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Sorting using order by"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Using limit and offset"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Subqueries"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Common table expressions"}],"type":"paragraph"}]}],"type":"unorderedList"},{"type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"Where","text":"Where"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"The ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftQL\/documentation\/SwiftQL\/GettingStarted","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"text":" showed ","type":"text"},{"code":"Where","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" clauses being used in select statements.","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"This section covers the capabilities of ","type":"text"},{"code":"Where","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" clauses in more detail.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"The result of a ","type":"text"},{"code":"Where","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" expression always resolves to a boolean value. Rows for","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"which the boolean value resolves to ","type":"text"},{"code":"true","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" are included in the result, and all","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"other rows are excluded.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"We have already seen a simple ","type":"text"},{"code":"Where","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" expression where we check if a field is","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"equal to a static value or a parameter:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["let query = sql { schema in","    let person = schema.table(Person.self)","    Select(person)","    From(person)","    Where(person.id == \"fred\")","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"A where expression can include multiple terms. SwiftQL does not impose any limit","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"on the complexity of the ","type":"text"},{"code":"Where","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" clause:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["let query = sql { schema in","    let person = schema.table(Person.self)","    Select(person)","    From(person)","    Where(person.id == \"fred\" || ((person.age > 21) && (person.age < 65))","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Refer to the ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftQL\/documentation\/SwiftQL\/Expressions","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"text":" guide for more details about expressions.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"Join","text":"Join"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"The ability to join tables in a query is where relational databases really start","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"to shine. SwiftQL supports cross join, inner join, and outer join.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"aside","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"SwiftQL does not currently support right joins."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"style":"note","name":"Note"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"First let’s define an ","type":"text"},{"code":"Occupation","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" table that we can join to our ","type":"text"},{"code":"Person","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" table:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["import SwiftQL","","@SQLTable struct Occupation {","    var id: String","    var name: String","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Let’s create the table and insert some entries:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["try database.makeRequest(with: sqlCreate(Occupation.self)).execute()","","let engineer = Occupation(id: \"eng\", name: \"Engineer\")","try database.makeRequest(with: sqlInsert(engineer)).execute()","","let scientist = Occupation(id: \"sci\", name: \"Scientist\")","try database.makeRequest(with: sqlInsert(scientist)).execute()"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Let’s also create some ","type":"text"},{"code":"Person","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" entries linked to these occupations:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["let joeBloggs = Person(id: \"joe-bloggs\", occupationId: \"eng\", name: \"Joe Bloggs\", age: \"25\")","try database.makeRequest(with: sqlInsert(joeBloggs)).execute()","","let janeDoe = Person(id: \"jane-doe\", occupationId: \"sci\", name: \"Jane Doe\", age: 45)","try database.makeRequest(with: sqlInsert(janeDoe)).execute()","","let davidSmith = Person(id: \"david-smith\", occupationId: \"sci\", name: \"David Smith\", age: 33)","try database.makeRequest(with: sqlInsert(davidSmith)).execute()"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"When joining multiple tables the result is often, although not always, a","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"combination of columns from some or or all of the tables. To define an result","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"with an arbitrary combination of columns we use a struct annotated with","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"code":"@SQLResult","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":".","type":"text"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["import SwiftQL","","@SQLResult PersonOccupation {","    let personId: String","    let personName: String","    let occupationId: String?","    let occupationName: String?","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"We can now write a query that selects all of the people in the database with","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"their occupation. The ","type":"text"},{"code":"occupationId","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" on the ","type":"text"},{"code":"Person","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" table is optional so when","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"we join the ","type":"text"},{"code":"Occupation","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" table it is possible that the ","type":"text"},{"code":"Occupation","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" table will","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"be ","type":"text"},{"code":"NULL","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" for that person. To handle this we need to tell SwiftQL that we expect","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"a ","type":"text"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"nullable"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"text":" table to be returned.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["let query = sql { schema in","    let person = schema.table(Person.self)","    let occupation = schema.nullableTable(Occupation.self)","    Select(","        PersonOccupation.columns(","            personId: person.id,","            occupationId: occupation.id,","            personName: person.name,","            occupationName: occupation.name","        )","    )","    From(person)","    Join.Left(occupation, on: occupation.id == person.occupationId)","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"We used the ","type":"text"},{"code":"PersonOccupation.columns","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" to instantiate a column set which","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"uses fields from both the ","type":"text"},{"code":"Person","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" and ","type":"text"},{"code":"Occupation","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" tables.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"We can also reference the fields of the result column set in the query:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["let query = sql { schema in","    let person = schema.table(Person.self)","    let occupation = schema.nullableTable(Occupation.self)","    let row = PersonOccupation.columns(","        personId: person.id,","        occupationId: occupation.id,","        personName: person.name,","        occupationName: occupation.name","    )","    Select(row)","    From(person)","    Join.Left(occupation, on: occupation.id == person.occupationId)","    Where(row.personName != \"Fred\")","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"aside","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"SwiftQL does not impose a limit on the  number of tables that can be"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"joined in a query."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"style":"tip","name":"Tip"},{"type":"aside","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Use "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Join.Cross"},{"type":"text","text":" or "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Join.Inner"},{"type":"text","text":" to perform a cross or inner"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"join respectively."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"style":"tip","name":"Tip"},{"type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"Group-By","text":"Group By"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Use the group by clause to return aggregate results, or results where a single","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"row has a computation from multiple records, such as the total number of records","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"matching some criteria.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Let’s define a ","type":"text"},{"code":"@SQLResult","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" to return the total number of people for each","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"occupation:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["import SwiftQL","","@SQLResult struct OccupationAggregate {","    var occupationId: String","    var numberOfPeople: Int","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"We can write a query to select the person records grouped by their","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"code":"occupationId","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":", and use the ","type":"text"},{"code":"count()","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" aggregate function to compute the number","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"of people for each occupation.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["let query = sql { schema in","    let person = schema.table(Person.self)","    let row = result {","        OccupationAggregate(","            occupationId: person.occupationId,","            numberOfPeople: person.id.count()","        )","    }","    Select(row)","    From(person)","    GroupBy(person.occupationId)","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"SwiftQL currently supports the following aggregate functions:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"table","header":"row","rows":[[[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Function"}],"type":"paragraph"}],[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Column type"}],"type":"paragraph"}],[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Usage"}],"type":"paragraph"}]],[[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"count()"}],"type":"paragraph"}],[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Any"}],"type":"paragraph"}],[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Number of items in the result set."}],"type":"paragraph"}]],[[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"min()"}],"type":"paragraph"}],[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Any comparable"}],"type":"paragraph"}],[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Minimum value in the result set."}],"type":"paragraph"}]],[[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"max()"}],"type":"paragraph"}],[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Any comparable"}],"type":"paragraph"}],[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Maximum value in the result set."}],"type":"paragraph"}]],[[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"average()"}],"type":"paragraph"}],[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Double"}],"type":"paragraph"}],[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Average (arithmetic mean) of values in the result set."}],"type":"paragraph"}]],[[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"sum()"}],"type":"paragraph"}],[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Int or Double"}],"type":"paragraph"}],[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Additive sum of values in the result set."}],"type":"paragraph"}]],[[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"groupConcat()"}],"type":"paragraph"}],[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"String"}],"type":"paragraph"}],[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Concatenation of all values in the result set."}]}]]]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"All of the aggregate functions accept a ","type":"text"},{"code":"distinct","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" boolean parameter. When set","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"to ","type":"text"},{"code":"true","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":", duplicate values will be discarded and only unique values will be","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"included in the result set.","type":"text"}]},{"style":"important","name":"Important","type":"aside","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"A group by clause must include at least one aggregate term. SwiftQL","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"currently does not enforce correctness of a query containing a group by clause.","type":"text"}]}]},{"type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"Having","text":"Having"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The having clause is used in conjunction with the group by clause to filter"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"groups. Think of like a where clause but operating on groups instead of"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"individual rows. As an example we can filter our previous query to only include"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"occupations where there are two or more people with that occupation:"}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["let query = sql { schema in","    let person = schema.table(Person.self)","    let row = result {","        OccupationAggregate(","            occupationId: person.occupationId,","            numberOfPeople: person.id.count()","        )","    }","    Select(row)","    From(person)","    GroupBy(person.occupationId)","    Having(row.numberOfPeople >= 2)","}"]},{"level":2,"anchor":"Order-By","text":"Order By","type":"heading"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Query results can be sorted using the order by clause. Use the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"ascending"},{"type":"text","text":" or"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"descending"},{"type":"text","text":" functions on the column or columns to sort by:"}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["let query = sql { schema in","    let person = schema.table(Person.self)","    Select(person)","    From(person)","    OrderBy(person.name.ascending())","}"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"To sort by multiple columns, include the columns in the order by clause:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["let query = sql { schema in","    let person = schema.table(Person.self)","    Select(person)","    From(person)","    OrderBy(person.name.ascending(), person.age.descending())","}"]},{"type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"Limit-and-offset","text":"Limit and offset"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Use the limit clause to specify the maximum number of items to return from a","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"query. We can write a query to return the five youngest people in the database:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["let query = sql { schema in","    let person = schema.table(Person.self)","    Select(person)","    From(person)","    OrderBy(person.age.ascending())","    Limit(5)"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The offset clause is used in conjunction with the limit clause. Offset skips a"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"number of rows, and is often used to paginate results from a large result set:"}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["let query = sql { schema in","    let person = schema.table(Person.self)","    Select(person)","    From(person)","    OrderBy(person.age.ascending())","    Limit(5)","    Offset(10)"]},{"type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"Subqueries","text":"Subqueries"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Subqueries can be used anywhere that a column is used, such as in a result for","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"a ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Select"},{"type":"text","text":" query:"}]},{"syntax":null,"code":["@SQLResult struct OccupationCount {","    let occupation: String","    let numberOfPeople: Int","}"],"type":"codeListing"},{"syntax":null,"code":["let query = sql { schema in","    let person = schema.table(Person.self)","    let occupation = schema.table(Occupation.self)","    Select(","        OccupationCount.columns(","            occupation: occupation.name,","            numberOfPeople: subqueryExpression { _ in","                Select(count(person.id))","                From(person)","                Where(person.occupationId == occupation.id)","            }","        )","    )","    From(occupation)","}"],"type":"codeListing"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Subqueries can also be used in place of a table in a "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"From"},{"type":"text","text":" or "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Joine"},{"text":" clause:","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"syntax":"swift","code":["let query = sql { schema in","    let person = schema.table(Person.self)","    Select(person)","    From(","        subqueryExpression { _ in","            Select(person)","            From(person)","            Where(person.age > 18)","        }","    )","    Where(person.age < 65)","}"],"type":"codeListing"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"See the "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftQL\/documentation\/SwiftQL\/Expressions#In-operator","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" documentation for an example of using a"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"subquery with the ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"in"},{"text":" operator.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"level":2,"text":"Union, Union All, Except, Intersect","type":"heading","anchor":"Union-Union-All-Except-Intersect"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"The result of two or more select statements can be combined into a compund query","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"using the union, union all, except, or intersect operators.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Suppose we have a table representing a family tree, and we want to select the","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"mother and father of each member in the tree.","type":"text"}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"We first define a table representing the family tree:"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"syntax":"swift","type":"codeListing","code":["@SQLTable struct Family {","    var name: String?","    var mom: String?","    var dad: String?","    var born: Date?","    var died: Date?","}"]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"We also define a result set for the name of the family member and their parent:"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"syntax":"swift","type":"codeListing","code":["@SQLResult struct FamilyMemberParent {","    let name: String?","    let parent: String?","}"]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"We can select the mother and father for each family member, then combine the"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"results using a "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"union"},{"type":"text","text":"."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"syntax":"swift","type":"codeListing","code":["let query = sql { schema in","    \/\/ Define the tables used in the two queries.","    let familyMom = schema.table(Family.self)","    let familyDad = schema.table(Family.self)","","    \/\/ Define the result that reads the person's name and their mother's name.","    let momRow = FamilyMemberParent.columns(name: familyMom.name, parent: familyMom.mom)","","    \/\/ Define the result that reads the person's name and their fathers's name.","    let dadRow = FamilyMemberParent.columns(name: familyDad.name, parent: familyDad.dad)","","    \/\/ Fetch the name of the mother for each person.","    Select(momRow)","    From(familyMom)","","    \/\/ Use union to append the results of the second query.","    Union()","","    \/\/ Fetch the name of the father for each person.","    Select(dadRow)","    From(familyDad)","}"]},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Using a ","type":"text"},{"code":"UnionAll","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":", the final result contains the combined results of the first","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"query followed by the results of the second query. A ","type":"text"},{"code":"Union","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" is similar except","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"duplicate rows are excluded.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"The ","type":"text"},{"code":"Except","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" operator returns the results from the first query that are not also","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"in the second query, which is to say that the row is omitted if it is returned","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"by both queries.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"The ","type":"text"},{"code":"Intersect","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" operator returns rows that are present in both queries.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"style":"tip","name":"Tip","type":"aside","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"All of the select statements used in an compound query must return the"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"same data type."}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"text":"Common table expressions","anchor":"Common-table-expressions","type":"heading","level":2},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Common table expressions are a powerful feature of SQLite which allow SQL to be","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"queried in a procedural way. Using common table expressions, SQL statements can","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"be encapsulated into separate expressions which can be used as tables in other","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"select statements within the same query.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"To use a common table expression:","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"orderedList","items":[{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Call the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"commonTableExpression"},{"type":"text","text":" function to create the common table"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"expression, passing a closure that returns a select query."}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Call the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"table"},{"type":"text","text":" function to identify the common table expression as a table."}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Call "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"with"},{"type":"text","text":" before "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"select"},{"type":"text","text":", to include the common table expression in"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"the query.","type":"text"}]}]}]},{"code":["let _ = sql { schema in","    let personCommonTable = schema.commonTableExpression { schema in","        let person = schema.table(Person.self)","        Select(person)","        From(person)","        Where(person.occupationId.notNull())","    }","    let person = schema.table(personCommonTable)","    With(personCommonTable)","    Select(person)","    From(person))"],"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"This is equivalent to the following SQL:"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"code":["WITH "," personCommonTable AS (","  SELECT","   person.*","  FROM","   Person AS person","  WHERE","   person.occupationId NOTNULL",")","SELECT"," person.*","FROM"," personCommonTable AS person"],"type":"codeListing","syntax":"sql"},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"A common table expression cannot be used direcly in a select, from, or join:","type":"text"}]}],"style":"note","type":"aside","name":"Note"},{"code":["let _ = select(personCommonTable) \/\/ Error, cannot select from common table expression "],"type":"codeListing","syntax":null},{"text":"Recursive common table expressions","anchor":"Recursive-common-table-expressions","type":"heading","level":3},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Recursive common table expressions are common table expressions where the query","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"refers to itself. They are commonly used with hierarchical data sets.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"A recursive expression is written as the union of two or more queries, where the","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"first query provides the base case, or starting condition, and the remaining","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"queries produce subsequent results.","type":"text"}]},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"To create a recursive common table expression use","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"code":"recursiveCommonTableExpression","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" to create.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"For our example let’s define a table to represent a hierarchical orag chart for","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"a company:","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"syntax":"swift","code":["@SQLTable struct Org {","    var name: String?","    var boss: String?","}"],"type":"codeListing"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"We will also define an ","type":"text"},{"code":"@SQLResult","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" that we use to refer to the result of the","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"recursive common table expression. This essentially defines a ‘table’ with a","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"single column.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"syntax":"swift","code":["@SQLResult struct ScalarString {","    var value: String","}"],"type":"codeListing"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"We can now create an expression which returns all of the members of the"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"organisation from a person named Alice, and everyone below her.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"We call ","type":"text"},{"code":"recursiveCommonTableExpression","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" passing the return type which is","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"returned by the expression. In this case we use our ","type":"text"},{"code":"ScalarString","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" result which","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"we defined above.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"recursiveCommonTableExpression"},{"type":"text","text":" closure provides a schema which we have"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"seen before, as well as a second parameter which we can use to refer to the","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"common table expression recursively.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"code":["let query = sql { schema in","","    let cte = schema.recursiveCommonTableExpression(ScalarString.self) { schema, cte in","        let org = schema.table(Org.self)","        \/\/ Define the initial value for the starting condition.","        let initialResult = ScalarString.columns(value: \"Alice\".toNullable())","        Select(initialResult)","        \/\/ Union the initial value with successive values.","        Union()","        \/\/ Select members from the org whose boss matches the current member","        Select(ScalarString.columns(value: org.name))","        From(org)","        Join.Cross(cte)","        Where(org.boss == cte.scalarValue)","    }","    ","    \/\/ Select members from the org whose names are returned by the common table expression.","    let org = schema.table(Org.self)","    With(cte)","    Select(org.name)","    From(org)","    Where(org.name.in(cte))","}"],"syntax":"swift","type":"codeListing"},{"level":3,"text":"Combining recusive common tables with non-recursive common tables","anchor":"Combining-recusive-common-tables-with-non-recursive-common-tables","type":"heading"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"When recursive common tables are used with other non-recursive common","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"tables, the recursive common table must appear after the other common tables in"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"the ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"With"},{"type":"text","text":" statement."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"We can now write a query to fetch all living ancestors of ‘Alice’, using the"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"family tree table from our earlier example:"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"code":["let selectStatement = sql { schema in","    ","    let parentOfCommonTable = schema.commonTableExpression { schema in","        let family = schema.table(Family.self)","        let momRow = FamilyMemberParent.columns(name: family.name, parent: family.mom)","        let dadRow = FamilyMemberParent.columns(name: family.name, parent: family.dad)","        Select(momRow)","        From(family)","        Union()","        Select(dadRow)","        From(family)","    }","    ","    let ancestorOfAliceCommonTable = schema.recursiveCommonTableExpression(ScalarString.self) { schema, this in","        let parentOf = schema.table(parentOfCommonTable)","        Select(ScalarString.columns(value: parentOf.parent))","        From(parentOf)","        Where(parentOf.name == \"Alice\".toNullable())","        UnionAll()","        Select(ScalarString.columns(value: parentOf.parent))","        From(parentOf)","        Join.Inner(this, on: this.value == parentOf.name)","    }","    ","    let ancestorOfAlice = schema.table(ancestorOfAliceCommonTable)","    let family = schema.table(Family.self)","    ","    \/\/ Note the order of the common tables. The recursive common table must appear after other common tables.","    With(parentOfCommonTable, ancestorOfAliceCommonTable)","    Select(family.name)","    From(ancestorOfAlice)","    Join.Cross(family)","    Where((ancestorOfAlice.value == family.name) && family.died.isNull())","    OrderBy(family.born.ascending())","}"],"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Observe the order of definitions. We define an ordinary common table which","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"selects the mother and  father for each family member. We then use this common","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"table in the recursive common table expression. In the with clause the the","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"recursive common table expression is placed last.","type":"text"}]},{"style":"warning","name":"Warning","type":"aside","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"SwiftQL does not currently enforce the order of common table","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"expressions in the with clause. It is the programmer’s responsibility to ensure","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"that the recursive common table expression is always placed last in the with","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"clause.","type":"text"}]}]}]}],"variants":[{"paths":["\/documentation\/swiftql\/queries"],"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}]}],"metadata":{"role":"article","title":"Select Queries","roleHeading":"Article","modules":[{"name":"SwiftQL"}]},"kind":"article","references":{"doc://SwiftQL/documentation/SwiftQL/GettingStarted":{"type":"topic","kind":"article","url":"\/documentation\/swiftql\/gettingstarted","role":"article","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftQL\/documentation\/SwiftQL\/GettingStarted","abstract":[{"text":"Introduces the basic concepts and usage of SwiftQL.","type":"text"}],"title":"Getting started"},"doc://SwiftQL/documentation/SwiftQL/Expressions#In-operator":{"title":"In operator","url":"\/documentation\/swiftql\/expressions#In-operator","kind":"section","abstract":[],"type":"topic","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftQL\/documentation\/SwiftQL\/Expressions#In-operator"},"doc://SwiftQL/documentation/SwiftQL":{"title":"SwiftQL","role":"collection","type":"topic","kind":"symbol","abstract":[],"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftQL\/documentation\/SwiftQL","url":"\/documentation\/swiftql"},"doc://SwiftQL/documentation/SwiftQL/Documentation":{"title":"SwiftQL","role":"collectionGroup","kind":"article","type":"topic","abstract":[{"text":"Write SQL using familiar type-safe Swift syntax.","type":"text"}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftQL\/documentation\/SwiftQL\/Documentation","url":"\/documentation\/swiftql\/documentation"},"doc://SwiftQL/documentation/SwiftQL/Expressions":{"type":"topic","title":"Expressions","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftQL\/documentation\/SwiftQL\/Expressions","abstract":[{"text":"In depth discussion of expressions in SwiftQL.","type":"text"}],"role":"article","url":"\/documentation\/swiftql\/expressions","kind":"article"}}}